</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810194" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6810194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810194/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" startId="3.[151,264,1390,1414]" targetBox="[153,1411,193,1351]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1390,1451]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,1390,1414]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">FIGURES 5–7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales, 2022" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales" authorityYear="2022" box="[320,506,1390,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[320,506,1390,1414]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Paravelia ameliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[512,569,1390,1414]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[512,569,1390,1414]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(5) Lateral habitus of male holotype, (6) fore femur and tibia of male holotype, showing grasping comb, (7) lateral habitus of female paratype. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 5 and 7.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1496,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,1496,1522]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Macropterous female.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[473,628,1496,1522]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">PARATYPES</typeStatus>
(n = 3), length 4.96–5.12 (mean = 5.02); maximum width (across humeral angles) 1.69–1.78 (mean = 1.75). Leg measurements as follows: fore leg, femur 1.17–1.19, tibia 1.18–1.26, tarsomeres 1–3, 0.05–0.07, 0.17–0.22, 0.28–0.37; middle leg, femur 1.38–1.54, tibia 1.48–1.62, tarsomeres 1–3, 0.08–0.09, 0.41–0.43, 0.42–0.43; hind leg, femur 1.67–1.83, tibia 2.01–2.10, tarsomeres 1–3, 0.10–0.16, 0.40–0.45, 0.43–0.44.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1496,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
Similar to male in general structure and coloration (
<figureCitation box="[785,894,1676,1702]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[220,1369,439,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-124@2.[204,1383,417,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (1) Dorsal and (2) ventral habitus of male holotype (UPTC). (3) Dorsal and (4) ventral habitus of female paratype (UPTC). Size bars = 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810192/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Figs. 3–4</figureCitation>
), except as follows: grasping comb of fore tibia distinctly shorter, 
<quantity box="[352,451,1712,1739]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" unit="mm" value="0.17">0.17 mm</quantity>
long, occupying only a small apical portion of segment (
<figureCitation box="[1083,1150,1712,1738]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1390,1414]" captionTargetBox="[153,1411,193,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,181,1366]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (5) Lateral habitus of male holotype, (6) fore femur and tibia of male holotype, showing grasping comb, (7) lateral habitus of female paratype. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 5 and 7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810194/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); hind femur without row of spines; hind tibia cylindrical, not clavate; lateral margins of abdomen not constricted at mid-length; posterior corner of laterotergite VII narrowly rounded to right-angled, not spinose; first gonocoxa without black denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="280" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1496,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1820,1846]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
This species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[927,975,1821,1847]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingRegion box="[1105,1362,1821,1847]" country="Colombia" name="Putumayo" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Putumayo Department</collectingRegion>
, Amazonian region of 
<collectingCountry box="[347,457,1856,1882]" name="Colombia" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[475,561,1856,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1975,1999]" captionTargetBox="[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-292@10.[298,1290,982,1951]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 30. Distribution records of five species of Paravelia in South America." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810204" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810204/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The specimens were collected on pools within the forest and a behavior of moving by small jumps was observed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1496,2027]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,1077]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1928,1954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished from congeners by the bicolored pronotum (dark-brown at basal two-thirds and light-brown posteriorly); the absence of distinct pruinosity or silvery patches on the anterior lobe of the pronotum; the basal macula of the forewing small and roughly ovate (
<figureCitation box="[1067,1174,2000,2026]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[220,1369,439,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-124@2.[204,1383,417,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (1) Dorsal and (2) ventral habitus of male holotype (UPTC). (3) Dorsal and (4) ventral habitus of female paratype (UPTC). Size bars = 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810192/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Figs. 1, 3</figureCitation>
); the grasping comb of the male fore tibia occupying more than half of the length of this segment (
<figureCitation box="[992,1061,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1390,1414]" captionTargetBox="[153,1411,193,1351]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,181,1366]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–7. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (5) Lateral habitus of male holotype, (6) fore femur and tibia of male holotype, showing grasping comb, (7) lateral habitus of female paratype. Size bar = 1.00 mm and applies only to Figs. 5 and 7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810194/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); the male hind femur with a row of 15 spines on the basal two-thirds (
<figureCitation box="[565,631,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[220,1369,439,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-124@2.[204,1383,417,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (1) Dorsal and (2) ventral habitus of male holotype (UPTC). (3) Dorsal and (4) ventral habitus of female paratype (UPTC). Size bars = 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810192/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); and the paramere notched basally on the dorsal surface (
<figureCitation box="[1286,1424,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1912,1936]" captionTargetBox="[152,1437,1102,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-432@4.[151,1437,1101,1889]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (8–10) Abdominal tergum VIII of male, (8) dorsal view, (9) ventral view, (10) lateral view. (11) Proctiger of male, dorsal view. (12) Genital capsule of male, lateral view (proctiger removed). (13) Paramere at a slightly different angle than in Fig. 12." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810196" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810196/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Figs. 12–13</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, this species exhibits sexual dimorphism in the body shape and in the hind tibial length, with males having a slightly constricted mid-abdominal region (
<figureCitation box="[739,803,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[220,1369,439,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-124@2.[204,1383,417,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Paravelia ameliae n. sp. (1) Dorsal and (2) ventral habitus of male holotype (UPTC). (3) Dorsal and (4) ventral habitus of female paratype (UPTC). Size bars = 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810192" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810192/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) and a hind tibia that is distinctly longer than in females (
<quantity box="[159,302,294,321]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4262" metricValueMax="6.5532" metricValueMin="6.2992" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="in" value="2.53" valueMax="2.58" valueMin="2.48">2.48–2.58 in</quantity>
males, 
<quantity box="[388,529,295,321]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2197" metricValueMax="5.334" metricValueMin="5.1053999999999995" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="in" value="2.0549999999999997" valueMax="2.1" valueMin="2.01">2.01–2.10 in</quantity>
females).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,435,330,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Comparing this species with its presumed closest relative within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1898" box="[1192,1302,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1192,1302,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult, mainly due to the absence of phylogenetic studies among the species of the genus. The new species described here does not have ocular setae, a characteristic shared with the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2021" box="[891,1001,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Callivelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[891,1001,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Callivelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus" authorityYear="1993" box="[1015,1129,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1015,1129,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Platyvelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus" authorityYear="1993" box="[1190,1314,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Steinovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1190,1314,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Steinovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales, 2022" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,268,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,268,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. ameliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[276,339,439,465]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[276,339,439,465]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
lacks other diagnostic features of these genera. Two other features present in the new species are shared with its bromeliad-inhabiting congeners, namely 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira, 2016" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2016" box="[786,1262,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bachmanni">
<emphasis box="[786,938,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. bachmanni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F." box="[946,1262,475,501]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" pagination="642 - 667" refId="ref7208" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. (2016) Four new species of Paravelia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) from Brazil, with notes on previously described species. Canadian Entomologist, 148, 642 - 667. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / tce. 2016.18" type="journal article" year="2016">Rodrigues &amp; Moreira, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira, 2016" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bromelicola">
<emphasis box="[1274,1436,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. bromelicola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F." box="[151,470,511,537]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" pagination="642 - 667" refId="ref7208" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. (2016) Four new species of Paravelia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) from Brazil, with notes on previously described species. Canadian Entomologist, 148, 642 - 667. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / tce. 2016.18" type="journal article" year="2016">Rodrigues &amp; Moreira, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Barbosa, 2011" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Barbosa" authorityYear="2011" box="[482,921,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae">
<emphasis box="[482,618,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. gabrielae</emphasis>
Moreira &amp; Barbosa, 2011
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1929)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[933,1281,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helenae">
<emphasis box="[933,1049,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. helenae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford, H. B." box="[1065,1273,511,537]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" pagination="759 - 761" refId="ref6612" refString="Hungerford, H. B. (1929) A new Velia from Arizona with notes on other species (Hemiptera-Veliidae). Annals of theEntomological Society of America, 22, 759 - 761. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 22.4.759" type="journal article" year="1929">Hungerford, 1929</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Drake, 1951)" baseAuthorityName="Drake" baseAuthorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="itatiayana">
<emphasis box="[1294,1437,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. itatiayana</emphasis>
(Drake, 1951)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus, 1984" authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Polhemus" authorityYear="1984" box="[327,831,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manausana">
<emphasis box="[327,485,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. manausana</emphasis>
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus, 1984
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Drake &amp; Harris, 1935)" baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[893,1278,546,573]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recens">
<emphasis box="[893,995,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. recens</emphasis>
(Drake &amp; Harris, 1935)
</taxonomicName>
: (1) the small posterior projection of the midline of the pronotum, and (2) the male hind tibia clavate. Since the bromeliadicolus species have some other characteristics absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales, 2022" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Moreira &amp; Morales" authorityYear="2022" box="[712,829,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[712,829,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. ameliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[837,901,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[837,901,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, such as the ocular setae, we believe that these two features probably evolved independently. In addition to differences in morphology, individuals of the new species were collected on pools, while the bromeliad-inhabiting species are restricted to the water pockets stored by the plants.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
Currently, only one species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1898" box="[546,656,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[546,656,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Paravelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[860,975,763,789]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Colombia</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[986,1087,763,788]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recens">
<emphasis box="[986,1087,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. recens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The others species previously recorded from the country were all transferred to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2019" box="[812,913,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Altavelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[812,913,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Altavelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus, D. A. &amp; Molano, F. &amp; Morales, I. &amp; Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Floriano, C. F. B." box="[971,1210,799,825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" pagination="295 - 314" refId="ref7021" refString="Polhemus, D. A., Molano, F., Morales, I., Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Floriano, C. F. B. (2019) Altavelia, a new genus of Neotropical Veliinae (Heteroptera: Gerromorpha: Veliidae), with a key to species and descriptions of four new species from Colombia. Zootaxa, 4585 (2), 295 - 314. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4585.2.4" type="journal article" year="2019">
Polhemus 
<emphasis box="[1088,1136,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
). The new species is easily separated from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[398,498,835,860]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recens">
<emphasis box="[398,498,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">P. recens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and all the other species of the genus based on the diagnostic characters mentioned above. Future phylogenetic studies may provide evidence of the species or lineage closest to this new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="281" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1077]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,907,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named in honor of Amelia Carvajal Morales, daughter of the last author of the present work.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
